<i>Amis</i> or from the feminine form, <i>Amice</i>. The Old French word <i>amis</i>, is from Latin <i>amicus</i> ‘friend’, which was used in Late Latin as a term for a man of the lower classes, in particular a slave. There were also derivatives of this as personal names, in particular masculine <i>Amicius</i> and feminine <i>Amicia</i>. Both were in use as personal names in England and may have contributed to the surname.","German: perhaps a nickname for an active person, from an ancient Germanic word related to Old High German <i>amazzig</i> ‘busy’.","Dutch: possibly a patronymic from <i>Ame</i> a common personal name in Holland and Friesland, an abbreviated form of an ancient Germanic personal name, perhaps beginning with <i>amel</i> ‘strong’."]},{"name":"Amison","meanings":["English: patronymic from   Amis   or   Ames  , meaning ‘son of <i>Amice</i> or <i>Ami</i>’."]},{"name":"Amos","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Amis  , assimilated in spelling to the Biblical name (see 2 below). It occurs chiefly in southeastern England.","Jewish, German, English, Scottish, and Welsh: from the Hebrew personal name <i>Amos</i>, of uncertain origin, in some traditions connected with the Hebrew verb <i>amos</i> ‘to carry’, and assigned the meaning ‘borne by God’. This was the name of a Biblical prophet of the 8th century  BC , whose oracles are recorded in the Book of Amos. This was one of the Biblical names taken up by Puritans and Nonconformists in the 16th–17th centuries, too late to have had much influence on surname formationm in Britain, except in Wales."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":51,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705202,"age":60,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705206,"age":73,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705207,"age":87,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"John Amis was born in 1498, in Essex, England. He had at least 1 daughter with Amy Amis. He died in 1592, in his hometown, at the age of 94."},"et":{"1498–1592":"1498–1592","1500–1574":"1500–1574","1520–1580":"1520–1580","1558":"1558","1500":"1500","1498":"1498","1520":"1520","1585":"1585","1574":"1574","1571":"1571","1592":"1592"," 1574":"1574","1580":"1580","1549":"1549","Essex, England":"Essex, England"},"fi":{"1498–1592":"1498–1592","1500–1574":"1500–1574","1520–1580":"1520–1580","1558":"1558","1500":"1500","1498":"14